<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">The Caterpillar Speaks in Tongues</DIV><br>
  <div align="center"><img src="images/caterpillar.jpg"><br>
  <a class="artistline" href="javascript:goauthor('jones');">art by Pat Jones</a></div><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>

<br><br>
 <br />
I can see each segment converse<br />
with the next, a Newton's Cradle <br />
of green pulp, a susurrus and hum<br />
<br />
of tiny hairs crossing and  uncrossing <br />
like rods in water-divination. <br />
I can almost hear the pin-leg <br />
<br />
plucks as rain. Each thrum<br />
of plump curve is a word entered<br />
into a dictionary of silences.<br />
<br /> 
Even voiceless, its spiracles gasp. <br />
It spools over thorny script, a mantra<br />
of prayers strung in a   twelve-bead rosary.<br />
<br />
<br><br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('midgley')">by James AL Midgley</a><br><br><br.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</div>
		
